// Ch5 Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting — IDs 1341–1490 (150 questions)
{id:1341,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the primary purpose of exit criteria in software testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"Exit criteria specify the conditions that must be satisfied before testing activities can be concluded, ensuring an objective basis for stopping testing."},
{id:1342,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is the BEST example of an exit criterion for a sprint?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"A well-defined sprint exit criterion includes completion of test execution and resolution of critical defects, giving a measurable quality gate."},
{id:1343,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, exit criteria are MOST closely related to which Agile concept?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"In Agile, exit criteria are captured in the Definition of Done (DoD), which defines what must be true for a story or sprint to be considered complete."},
{id:1344,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team discovers that their exit criteria are consistently met too easily, with testing concluding before adequate quality is achieved. What should they do?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"If exit criteria are met too easily without achieving adequate quality, they should be tightened with more meaningful, measurable thresholds."},
{id:1345,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team has the following exit criterion: '80% of test cases pass.' A tester argues this criterion is insufficient. Which argument is MOST valid?",options:["A. The criterion should specify 100% pass rate regardless of context","B. The criterion does not account for which test cases failed â€” critical failures may still be open","C. The criterion should measure lines of code instead of test cases","D. The criterion is valid as long as the product owner agrees"],answer:1,explanation:"A pass-rate percentage alone is insufficient because critical or high-severity failures may be among the failing 20%, making the product unreleasable."},
{id:1346,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which combination of exit criteria provides the STRONGEST quality gate before a production release?",options:["A. All user stories accepted by the product owner only","B. Code review complete and unit tests passing only","C. All critical defects resolved, code coverage threshold met, performance benchmarks passed, and product owner acceptance obtained","D. Sprint retrospective completed and velocity maintained"],answer:2,explanation:"A strong release quality gate combines defect resolution, coverage thresholds, non-functional benchmarks, and business acceptance â€” no single criterion is sufficient alone."},
{id:1347,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A regulatory-domain Agile team must demonstrate compliance at each release. Their exit criteria include traceability from requirements to test results. A new auditor states that traceability alone is insufficient. Which ADDITIONAL criterion would BEST satisfy the auditor?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Regulatory compliance requires not just traceability but evidence of test execution, defect resolution, and independent review â€” all documented and auditable."},
{id:1348,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team uses risk-based exit criteria. During a sprint, a previously low-risk area is found to have a high defect rate. What is the CORRECT response according to risk-based testing principles?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Risk-based testing is dynamic. New evidence of higher defect rates requires re-evaluating risk and adjusting exit criteria and test effort to match the updated risk profile."},
{id:1349,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does test completion mean in the context of a sprint?",options:["A. All code has been deployed to production","B. All planned testing activities for the sprint have been finished and results recorded","C. The test manager has signed the test plan","D. All defects have been assigned to developers"],answer:1,explanation:"Test completion means all planned testing activities are finished, results are documented, and any agreed exit criteria have been evaluated."},
{id:1350,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which document is typically produced at the end of a testing phase to summarize testing activities and results?",options:["A. Test plan","B. Test case specification","C. Test summary report","D. Defect report"],answer:2,explanation:"A test summary report is produced at the end of a testing phase, summarizing what was tested, results, defects, and whether exit criteria were met."},
{id:1351,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, test completion at the sprint level is BEST indicated by:",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"In Agile, completion of each story against the Definition of Done â€” which includes testing â€” is the clearest indicator of sprint-level test completion."},
{id:1352,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team finishes executing all test cases but has 5 open medium-severity defects. According to typical exit criteria, what should happen?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Open defects must be evaluated against exit criteria. Medium defects may or may not block completion depending on defined thresholds and product risk."},
{id:1353,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester is asked to confirm test completion for a release. The test execution is 100% complete but code coverage is only 62% against a target of 75%. What should the tester conclude?",options:["A. Test completion is achieved because all test cases ran","B. Test completion is not achieved because the coverage exit criterion has not been met","C. Test completion depends solely on the product owner's decision","D. Coverage metrics are irrelevant to test completion"],answer:1,explanation:"Test completion requires all defined exit criteria to be met. If a coverage threshold is part of those criteria and is not met, testing is not complete."},
{id:1354,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following activities is performed DURING test completion, as opposed to during test execution?",options:["A. Executing regression test scripts","B. Logging new defects found in exploratory testing","C. Archiving test assets, documenting lessons learned, and confirming exit criteria are met","D. Writing test cases for new user stories"],answer:2,explanation:"Test completion activities include archiving test assets, documenting lessons learned, handing over test materials, and verifying exit criteria â€” not execution activities."},
{id:1355,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team operating in a safety-critical domain must demonstrate that test completion is valid for a regulatory body. Which evidence set is MOST comprehensive?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Safety-critical regulatory bodies require documented, auditable evidence: execution records, defect status, requirements traceability, coverage data, and independent review."},
{id:1356,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the main purpose of a test progress report in Agile?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Test progress reports give stakeholders transparent, timely visibility into testing status, what has been done, what remains, and any risks or blockers."},
{id:1357,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Agile teams, which format is MOST preferred for communicating test status to the team?",options:["A. A 30-page formal test status report submitted monthly","B. Lightweight, visible information radiators updated frequently","C. Emails sent to the project sponsor weekly","D. Formal gate review presentations every sprint"],answer:1,explanation:"Agile favors lightweight, visible, continuously updated communication mechanisms like task boards and information radiators over heavy formal reports."},
{id:1358,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"medium",question:"A test report shows that 95% of test cases have passed but the defect removal efficiency is only 40%. What does this indicate?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Low defect removal efficiency means many defects are not being caught during testing and are escaping to production, regardless of how many test cases pass."},
{id:1359,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following items should be included in an Agile test summary report?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"A test summary report includes scope of testing, results, defect summary, and exit criteria evaluation â€” focused information for decision-making."},
{id:1360,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"hard",question:"A stakeholder asks why the test report shows 90% test case pass rate but production defects are still high. Which concept BEST explains this discrepancy?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"High pass rates can be misleading if test cases don't reflect real usage patterns or if test data doesn't match production data â€” coverage gaps allow defects to escape."},
{id:1361,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"hard",question:"In an Agile context, a tester must report on testing to multiple stakeholders with different needs: developers, product owner, and the release manager. The BEST approach is:",options:["A. Write one detailed technical report and send it to all stakeholders","B. Tailor the level of detail and focus of reporting to each stakeholder's perspective and decision-making needs","C. Report only to the product owner and let them cascade information","D. Avoid reporting until the end of the release"],answer:1,explanation:"Effective test reporting tailors content and detail to the audience. Developers need defect details; product owners need business risk summaries; release managers need go/no-go data."},
{id:1362,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team's test report consistently shows green status, but a post-release audit reveals repeated production incidents. A root-cause analysis finds that the test report metrics were all technically accurate. What is the MOST LIKELY systemic failure?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"This is the 'metric trap' â€” teams can report accurate but misleading metrics that measure activity (tests run, cases passed) rather than quality outcomes (risk coverage, defect detection effectiveness)."},
{id:1363,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which metric directly measures the quality of a software product during testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Defects found per feature area is a direct quality metric â€” it reveals where quality problems are concentrated in the product."},
{id:1364,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does 'defect removal efficiency' (DRE) measure?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"DRE = (defects found pre-release) / (total defects) Ã— 100. High DRE means testing is catching most defects before they reach production."},
{id:1365,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team tracks 'escaped defects' as a quality metric. What does this metric represent?",options:["A. Defects that were cancelled without being fixed","B. Defects discovered by customers or in production that were not caught during testing","C. Defects that were deferred to the backlog","D. Defects found during exploratory testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Escaped defects are defects that slip through testing and are found in production or by end users â€” a critical quality metric indicating testing effectiveness."},
{id:1366,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team wants to measure the cost of quality. Which of the following is classified as a 'cost of poor quality'?",options:["A. Time spent writing automated tests","B. Cost of test environment setup","C. Customer support costs due to production defects and rework costs","D. Cost of hiring a test automation engineer"],answer:2,explanation:"Cost of poor quality includes costs incurred because quality was not achieved: rework, customer support, incident response â€” all are failure costs."},
{id:1367,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's defect density increases each sprint but their velocity remains stable. What does this pattern MOST LIKELY indicate?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Stable velocity with rising defect density is a classic technical debt warning sign â€” the team is delivering but the code quality is degrading, making each change riskier."},
{id:1368,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which quality metric would BEST help an Agile team decide whether to add more testing effort to a specific module?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"High defect density combined with high change frequency identifies modules with the greatest quality risk â€” the best targets for additional testing effort."},
{id:1369,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team uses multiple quality metrics. Over three sprints: defect density is low, DRE is high, escaped defects are low, but customer satisfaction scores are falling. What does this combination MOST LIKELY indicate?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"When technical quality metrics are positive but customer satisfaction falls, the gap is usually in non-functional areas (usability, performance, fit-for-purpose) not captured by current tests."},
{id:1370,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does code coverage measure?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Code coverage measures what proportion of the source code (statements, branches, paths) is exercised when the test suite runs."},
{id:1371,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which coverage metric checks whether both the true and false outcomes of every conditional statement have been tested?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Branch coverage (also called decision coverage) verifies that both the true and false outcomes of each decision point in the code have been exercised."},
{id:1372,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team achieves 100% statement coverage. A tester states this does not guarantee all bugs are found. Why is the tester correct?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"100% statement coverage is a weak criterion â€” it simply means every line ran once. Many defects hide in specific decision branches or data combinations not covered by the test suite."},
{id:1373,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, requirements coverage is tracked to ensure:",options:["A. Every line of code has a corresponding test","B. Every user story and acceptance criterion has at least one test case verifying it","C. All non-functional requirements are deferred to the final sprint","D. Testers have reviewed all code commits"],answer:1,explanation:"Requirements coverage ensures traceability â€” every user story and acceptance criterion is covered by at least one test, providing confidence that all agreed functionality is verified."},
{id:1374,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's requirements coverage is 100% but their risk-based coverage is only 55%. What is the MOST significant implication?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Requirements coverage and risk coverage measure different things. Low risk-based coverage means the most critical areas are not adequately tested, regardless of functional requirements coverage."},
{id:1375,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following statements about coverage metrics is TRUE in an Agile context?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Coverage metrics are useful indicators but not sufficient alone. Agile release decisions combine coverage data with defect status, business risk, and stakeholder acceptance."},
{id:1376,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team achieves 85% branch coverage and 90% requirements coverage. The product owner wants to release. A tester identifies that the remaining 15% uncovered branches are in the payment processing module. What is the CORRECT action?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Coverage numbers must be interpreted in context. Uncovered code in a high-risk, high-impact module (payments) represents far greater risk than the same gap in a low-risk area, requiring explicit risk acceptance."},
{id:1377,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does 'defect age' measure in a testing context?",options:["A. The severity level of a defect","B. The time elapsed from defect discovery to defect resolution","C. The number of defects found in a sprint","D. The version of the software in which a defect was introduced"],answer:1,explanation:"Defect age measures how long a defect has been open â€” from when it was logged to when it was resolved. Long defect age can indicate process bottlenecks."},
{id:1378,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Agile testing, which defect metric helps the team prioritize which defects to fix first?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Defect severity (impact on the system) and priority (urgency of fixing) together guide which defects the team should address first."},
{id:1379,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team tracks the 'defect arrival rate' during a sprint. This metric is used to:",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Defect arrival rate tracks how many new defects are found over time. A rising rate late in testing is a warning sign that the product is not stabilizing."},
{id:1380,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does a 'defect resolution rate' that is consistently lower than the defect arrival rate indicate?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"When resolution rate < arrival rate, the open defect count grows each sprint â€” a sign the team cannot keep up with quality issues, risking an ever-growing defect backlog."},
{id:1381,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team analyzes defect distribution and finds that 80% of defects come from 20% of the modules. How should this information influence their testing strategy?",options:["A. Remove the defect-prone modules from scope","B. Apply the Pareto principle â€” focus additional test effort and quality improvement activities on the defect-prone 20% of modules","C. Distribute test effort evenly regardless of defect distribution","D. Assign the 20% of modules to a separate team"],answer:1,explanation:"Pareto analysis of defect distribution guides risk-based testing â€” concentrating effort on defect-prone areas maximizes defect detection with available time and resources."},
{id:1382,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester notices that the number of reopened defects is increasing each sprint. What does this MOST LIKELY indicate?",options:["A. Testers are being too strict in their verification","B. Developers are fixing defects correctly but testers are reopening for trivial reasons","C. Root cause analysis of defects is insufficient, leading to fixes that address symptoms rather than underlying causes","D. The test environment is unstable"],answer:2,explanation:"Rising reopened defect rates typically indicate superficial fixes â€” developers are fixing the symptom but not the root cause, causing defects to recur."},
{id:1383,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile release has: 0 critical defects open, 3 high defects open (all with approved workarounds), DRE of 94%, and 2 escaped defects from the previous release. The product owner asks if this represents acceptable quality for release. What is the MOST complete analysis?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"A holistic release readiness assessment requires evaluating all metrics together. The profile is largely positive but escaped defects from the prior release demand confirmation that the gaps were addressed."},
{id:1384,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the primary audience for a test summary report?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Test summary reports are decision-support documents aimed at stakeholders â€” management, product owners, and release managers â€” who need quality information to make go/no-go decisions."},
{id:1385,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is a standard section found in a test summary report?",options:["A. Developer code review comments","B. Summary of testing scope, results, defect statistics, and evaluation against exit criteria","C. The product's marketing strategy","D. The team's personal development goals"],answer:1,explanation:"A standard test summary report covers: testing scope and objectives, what was tested, results summary, defect statistics, exit criteria evaluation, and conclusions/recommendations."},
{id:1386,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team produces a test summary report at the end of a release. The report states 'all tests passed.' A reviewer says this statement alone is insufficient. Why?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"'All tests passed' is meaningless without context: How many tests? What was covered? Were risks adequately addressed? What was the defect history? A good report provides this context."},
{id:1387,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, test summary reports are MOST useful when they:",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Agile values short feedback loops and transparency. Lightweight sprint-level and release-level summary reports shared openly enable timely decision-making."},
{id:1388,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"hard",question:"A test summary report recommends against releasing a product due to unresolved high-severity defects. The product owner overrides the recommendation and releases anyway. What should the tester document?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"When a release proceeds despite quality concerns, the tester's responsibility is to document the residual risk, open defects, and the authorized decision â€” providing an audit trail and risk record."},
{id:1389,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following makes a test summary report MOST actionable for future sprints?",options:["A. A list of all test cases with their status","B. A lessons-learned section identifying what testing approaches worked, what did not, and specific process improvements recommended","C. The names of all team members who participated in testing","D. The exact times when each test was executed"],answer:1,explanation:"Lessons learned and process improvement recommendations make the summary report forward-looking and actionable, driving continuous improvement in future sprints."},
{id:1390,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A test summary report for a regulated medical device release must satisfy both Agile team needs and regulatory body requirements. Which approach BEST balances these needs?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"A tiered report structure satisfies both audiences: lightweight summaries for Agile decision-making and detailed formal appendices for regulatory compliance â€” without duplicating effort."},
{id:1391,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the purpose of a sprint exit review in the context of testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"The sprint exit review (sprint review) evaluates whether completed work meets the DoD, which includes testing activities â€” it is a quality gate at the sprint level."},
{id:1392,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Scrum, what happens to a user story that does not meet the Definition of Done at sprint end?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Incomplete stories that don't meet the DoD are returned to the product backlog â€” they are not 'done' and must not be counted in sprint velocity."},
{id:1393,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team's Definition of Done includes: unit tests passing, code reviewed, integration tests passing, and acceptance tests signed off. At sprint end, two stories pass all criteria except acceptance test sign-off. What is the correct action?",options:["A. Mark them as done â€” most of the criteria are met","B. Do not mark them as done â€” the DoD must be fully met for a story to be considered complete","C. Move the sign-off to the next sprint and count the stories as done now","D. Remove acceptance test sign-off from the DoD to avoid this situation"],answer:1,explanation:"The DoD is binary â€” all criteria must be met. Partial completion does not count as done. This protects sprint integrity and prevents accumulating undone work."},
{id:1394,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why is a strong Definition of Done important for exit criteria evaluation in Agile?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"A well-defined DoD creates an objective exit criterion for every story â€” preventing disputes about whether work is complete and ensuring consistent quality standards."},
{id:1395,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team discovers near the end of a sprint that meeting the full DoD for all stories would require an additional two days. Which response aligns BEST with Agile principles?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Agile timeboxes are fixed. The correct response is to reduce scope â€” complete fewer stories fully rather than all stories partially. Never compromise the DoD."},
{id:1396,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team has a DoD that includes 'no known critical defects.' At sprint end, one critical defect is found in a story. What impact does this have on the sprint exit decision?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"A critical defect violates the DoD for that specific story. The story is incomplete. The sprint closes on time but the affected story returns to the backlog for completion."},
{id:1397,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team's DoD has evolved over 12 sprints and now includes 47 separate criteria. Sprint exit evaluations take half a day per sprint. A coach points out this is a problem. Why, and what should be done?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"A bloated DoD is a quality theater anti-pattern. The DoD should be lean, valuable, and executable within sprint rhythms. Rationalization focuses it on criteria that genuinely drive quality outcomes."},
{id:1398,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does 'release readiness' mean in an Agile context?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Release readiness means the increment meets defined quality thresholds, exit criteria are satisfied, and stakeholders have agreed the product is suitable for production deployment."},
{id:1399,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which role in Scrum has the authority to decide whether a product increment is released to production?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"In Scrum, the Product Owner owns the product backlog and decides what gets released â€” they are accountable for the value and timing of releases."},
{id:1400,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"medium",question:"A release readiness review identifies the following: all critical defects resolved, performance benchmarks met, regression suite passing at 97%, and 3 low-severity cosmetic defects open. What is the MOST appropriate conclusion?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Release readiness requires holistic assessment. All major criteria are met; 3 cosmetic defects represent acceptable residual risk that can be formally accepted or scheduled for a minor fix."},
{id:1401,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is a release readiness criterion specifically relevant to Agile teams doing continuous delivery?",options:["A. A 6-month regression test cycle has been completed","B. The automated regression suite passes in the CI/CD pipeline for the current build","C. A formal test plan has been approved by the steering committee","D. All developers have completed mandatory training"],answer:1,explanation:"In continuous delivery, automated regression tests running in the CI/CD pipeline serve as the primary release readiness gate â€” fast, repeatable, and integrated into the delivery pipeline."},
{id:1402,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"hard",question:"A product owner declares release readiness after sprint 8, but the tester's release readiness checklist reveals 2 unresolved high-severity defects. What is the tester's MOST appropriate action?",options:["A. Accept the product owner's decision without raising concerns","B. Immediately halt all development work","C. Formally document the open defects and their risk, present the findings to the product owner and relevant stakeholders, and ensure the risk acceptance decision is recorded","D. Fix the defects themselves without involving the development team"],answer:2,explanation:"The tester's role is to provide objective quality information. Formally documenting open defects and escalating to stakeholders enables informed risk acceptance â€” not unilateral blocking or silence."},
{id:1403,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is a 'release readiness review' and what outputs should it produce?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"A release readiness review systematically evaluates quality evidence against release criteria, producing a documented go/no-go recommendation with clear rationale and identified residual risks."},
{id:1404,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A team releases a product increment that passes all defined release readiness criteria. Two days post-release, a critical production incident occurs in a feature area that had 100% test coverage. How should the team respond, and what does this situation reveal about their release readiness process?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Coverage of test cases â‰  coverage of real-world risk scenarios. Post-mortems that identify what was missing from test scenarios drive genuine improvement in release readiness criteria."},
{id:1405,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is 'residual risk' in the context of software testing?",options:["A. Risk that has been completely eliminated by testing","B. Risk that remains after all planned testing and mitigation activities have been completed","C. The risk of running out of test cases","D. Risk associated with the test environment only"],answer:1,explanation:"Residual risk is the risk that remains after testing and mitigation. No testing eliminates all risk â€” residual risk must be acknowledged, assessed, and formally accepted before release."},
{id:1406,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"Who is responsible for formally accepting residual risk before a product release?",options:["A. The lead tester","B. The Scrum Master","C. The appropriate business stakeholder or product owner","D. The CI/CD pipeline automation"],answer:2,explanation:"Residual risk acceptance is a business decision. The product owner or appropriate business stakeholder must formally accept the remaining risk before the product is released."},
{id:1407,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team has tested extensively but 12 user stories remain untested due to time constraints. How should this residual risk be handled?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Residual risk from untested items must be documented, assessed for impact, and formally accepted by the appropriate decision-maker â€” not ignored or hidden."},
{id:1408,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is an example of a residual risk mitigation strategy AFTER testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Post-release residual risk mitigation includes enhanced monitoring, alerting, and incident response plans that reduce the impact of defects that escape to production."},
{id:1409,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester produces a residual risk report showing that 3 high-priority functional areas received less than 30% risk-based coverage due to sprint time constraints. What should this report trigger?",options:["A. Immediate cancellation of the project","B. A structured risk discussion with stakeholders to decide whether to delay release, accept the risk with mitigations, or target additional testing in the next sprint","C. Automatic release â€” time constraints are always an acceptable reason for low coverage","D. Replacement of the testing team"],answer:1,explanation:"A residual risk report is an input to a risk acceptance decision. Stakeholders must consciously decide between releasing with known risk, mitigating further, or delaying â€” not ignore the information."},
{id:1410,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"In a risk-based testing approach, how is residual risk calculated?",options:["A. Residual risk = original risk Ã— (1 - test coverage percentage)","B. Residual risk = number of open defects Ã— sprint velocity","C. Residual risk = initial risk level minus the risk reduction achieved through testing and mitigation activities","D. Residual risk = total lines of code divided by number of test cases"],answer:2,explanation:"Residual risk is the remaining risk after mitigation. It is calculated as initial risk minus the reduction achieved through testing, defect fixing, and other risk treatment activities."},
{id:1411,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A risk register shows 15 identified risks. After testing, 10 risks have been fully mitigated, 3 are partially mitigated with accepted residual exposure, and 2 remain unaddressed due to scope exclusions. Before release, the product owner accepts all residual risks verbally. What is STILL missing from a governance perspective?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Governance requires documented risk acceptance â€” verbal agreements leave no audit trail. Written records of who accepted which risks, when, and under what conditions are essential for accountability."},
{id:1412,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"easy",question:"What are acceptance criteria in Agile development?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Acceptance criteria are specific, testable conditions defined for each user story that must be satisfied for the story to be considered complete and accepted by the product owner."},
{id:1413,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"easy",question:"Who is primarily responsible for defining acceptance criteria for user stories in Scrum?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"The Product Owner is primarily responsible for defining acceptance criteria, though collaboration with developers and testers (three amigos) improves their quality and testability."},
{id:1414,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"medium",question:"A tester finds that a user story has been implemented correctly but one acceptance criterion has not been verified. According to the Definition of Done, what should happen?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"All acceptance criteria must be verified for a story to meet the DoD. Partial verification means the story is not complete and must return to the backlog."},
{id:1415,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the 'three amigos' practice and how does it relate to acceptance criteria evaluation?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Three amigos brings together business, development, and testing perspectives to ensure acceptance criteria are clear, complete, and testable before development starts â€” reducing rework."},
{id:1416,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"hard",question:"Acceptance criteria for a story state: 'The page must load in under 3 seconds.' Testing shows it loads in 2.8 seconds on the test environment but 4.2 seconds in production. How should this be evaluated?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Acceptance criteria must be evaluated under representative conditions. Test environment results that differ significantly from production are insufficient â€” production-representative testing is required."},
{id:1417,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"hard",question:"A product owner writes vague acceptance criteria such as 'the system should be fast and easy to use.' A tester flags this as a problem. What is the CORRECT reason?",options:["A. Acceptance criteria should not mention usability or performance","B. Vague acceptance criteria cannot be objectively tested or evaluated â€” they must be specific and measurable to serve as valid exit criteria","C. Only developers should evaluate performance and usability criteria","D. Acceptance criteria are only for functional requirements"],answer:1,explanation:"Vague acceptance criteria like 'fast' and 'easy to use' are untestable. Acceptance criteria must be specific and measurable (e.g., 'page loads in <3 seconds on standard hardware') to be meaningful exit criteria."},
{id:1418,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team uses Behavior-Driven Development (BDD). Their acceptance criteria are written as Gherkin scenarios (Given/When/Then). At sprint exit, all BDD scenarios pass. A stakeholder still rejects the stories. What is the MOST LIKELY root cause?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Passing BDD scenarios only proves the system does what the scenarios specify. If those scenarios don't reflect true stakeholder needs (due to poor requirements collaboration), the product can pass all tests yet fail to meet expectations."},
{id:1419,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following is an example of a non-functional test?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Non-functional testing evaluates qualities like performance, scalability, security, and reliability â€” not specific functional behaviors. Load testing under concurrent users is non-functional."},
{id:1420,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"In Agile, when should non-functional testing occur?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Agile integrates non-functional testing throughout the project. Waiting until the end creates risk and increases cost of fixing issues. Each sprint should include relevant non-functional testing."},
{id:1421,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why are non-functional requirements difficult to include in Agile sprints?",options:["A. Non-functional requirements are never relevant to Agile projects","B. Non-functional characteristics like performance and security often span multiple features and are hard to attribute to a single story â€” they require special handling in the backlog","C. Non-functional testing requires waterfall methodology","D. Agile teams are not allowed to do non-functional testing"],answer:1,explanation:"Non-functional requirements are cross-cutting concerns that don't map neatly to single stories. They require separate backlog items, dedicated sprint capacity, or specific testing sprints."},
{id:1422,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"An Agile team discovers a significant performance regression in sprint 7 that was present since sprint 3. Why did they not detect it earlier, and what should they change?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Performance regressions caught late are expensive to fix. Automated performance tests in CI/CD pipelines catch regressions at the sprint level when they are introduced, not sprints later."},
{id:1423,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"Exit criteria for a release include: 'System must sustain 500 concurrent users with average response time <2 seconds.' Performance testing shows 450 concurrent users met with <2 second response, but 500 users causes 2.4 second average response. What is the correct release decision?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Exit criteria are binary gates. If the criterion specifies 500 users at <2 seconds and the system achieves 450, the criterion is not met. A formal revision or fix is required â€” not an informal judgment call."},
{id:1424,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following non-functional quality characteristics is MOST relevant to evaluating security exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Security exit criteria should be evaluated using evidence from penetration testing, vulnerability assessments, and compliance checks against recognized security standards."},
{id:1425,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team must release a financial platform. Non-functional exit criteria include: availability 99.9%, RTO <4 hours, RPO <1 hour, and MTTR <2 hours. Testing confirms availability and RTO. RPO cannot be verified due to test environment limitations, and MTTR was not tested. What is the correct approach?",options:["A. Release since 2 out of 4 non-functional criteria are verified","B. Unverified exit criteria (RPO and MTTR) represent unacceptable residual risk for a financial platform; the team must either conduct the tests in a representative environment, formally accept the risk with documented justification, or delay release","C. Non-functional criteria are always optional for financial platforms","D. Estimate RPO and MTTR based on the verified metrics and assume they are acceptable"],answer:1,explanation:"For safety-critical financial systems, unverified non-functional exit criteria represent serious risk. Untested RPO and MTTR cannot be assumed to be acceptable â€” they require testing, formal risk acceptance, or release deferral."},
{id:1426,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the difference between entry criteria and exit criteria in testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Entry criteria are preconditions for starting a testing activity (e.g., build available, environment ready). Exit criteria are the conditions that must be met to conclude testing. They are complementary but distinct."},
{id:1427,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team defines exit criteria as '100% of planned test cases executed.' A tester argues that execution rate alone is a poor exit criterion. Which argument BEST supports the tester's position?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Execution rate is an activity metric, not a quality metric. A test suite where 100% of cases are executed but 40% fail, or where critical risks are untested, does not represent adequate exit."},
{id:1428,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"hard",question:"Which of the following scenarios represents PREMATURE test completion?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Premature test completion occurs when testing is stopped based on time constraints rather than quality evidence â€” leaving critical defects unresolved and stories untested."},
{id:1429,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"hard",question:"A tester is preparing a report for an executive who will make the go/no-go release decision. What should the report focus on?",options:["A. Full technical details of every test case, including test data and expected vs. actual results","B. A concise business-risk-focused summary: quality status against exit criteria, key open risks, recommendation, and the information needed to make an informed go/no-go decision","C. The team's daily test execution logs for the entire sprint","D. Technical debt and refactoring backlog items"],answer:1,explanation:"Executive-level reports must be concise and business-focused â€” highlighting quality against criteria, open risks, and a clear recommendation. Technical details belong in appendices."},
{id:1430,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the difference between a 'lagging indicator' and a 'leading indicator' in quality metrics?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Leading indicators (complexity, coverage trends, defect arrival rate) help teams act before quality problems materialize. Lagging indicators (escaped defects, customer incidents) confirm problems after they occur."},
{id:1431,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team achieves high requirements coverage but a security audit reveals significant vulnerabilities. What does this indicate about their coverage approach?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Different coverage types address different risk dimensions. Functional requirements coverage doesn't substitute for security coverage â€” exit criteria must include coverage across all relevant quality dimensions."},
{id:1432,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does a 'defect leakage' metric specifically measure?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Defect leakage measures the proportion of defects that were not caught at a given testing stage and were found later â€” indicating the effectiveness of testing at each phase."},
{id:1433,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which Scrum ceremony is MOST directly related to evaluating whether sprint exit criteria have been met?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"The Sprint Review is where the team demonstrates completed work, evaluates stories against the DoD, and the product owner accepts or rejects the increment â€” directly equivalent to sprint exit evaluation."},
{id:1434,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"hard",question:"An organization practices continuous deployment. In this context, how do release readiness criteria function differently compared to a traditional release?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Continuous deployment embeds release readiness criteria as automated quality gates â€” build passes tests, passes coverage thresholds, passes security scans â€” before each stage, making readiness evaluation continuous and automated."},
{id:1435,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why is documenting residual risk important even when stakeholders have verbally accepted it?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Documenting residual risk is a governance and knowledge management imperative. It creates accountability, supports future decision-making, and ensures institutional memory of known quality limitations."},
{id:1436,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is 'acceptance test-driven development' (ATDD)?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"ATDD defines acceptance tests before coding begins. This aligns development to testable acceptance criteria and ensures the team has a shared, verifiable definition of what 'done' looks like."},
{id:1437,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"How should non-functional testing be represented in an Agile product backlog?",options:["A. Non-functional requirements should never be in the product backlog","B. As explicit backlog items (stories, spikes, or enablers) with measurable acceptance criteria, prioritized alongside functional stories","C. As a separate document maintained outside the backlog","D. As a single backlog item at the very end of the release"],answer:1,explanation:"Non-functional requirements must be explicit, prioritized backlog items with measurable acceptance criteria â€” treating them as afterthoughts leads to late discovery of quality issues."},
{id:1438,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the risk of having no defined exit criteria for a testing phase?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Without defined exit criteria, there is no objective basis for deciding when to stop testing â€” testing may go on forever or stop too early, driven by time pressure rather than quality evidence."},
{id:1439,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"hard",question:"A test summary report for an Agile release should include 'test coverage against risks.' Why is this important?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Risk-based coverage reporting connects testing effort to business risk â€” showing stakeholders not just what was tested, but whether the highest-risk areas received appropriate attention."},
{id:1440,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is 'mean time to detect' (MTTD) a measure of in testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"MTTD measures the lag between when a defect is introduced and when it is detected. Lower MTTD means testing detects issues sooner â€” reducing the cost and impact of defects."},
{id:1441,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is NOT a good example of a testable exit criterion?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"'Feels good enough' is a subjective judgment, not a testable criterion. Valid exit criteria must be specific, measurable, and objectively verifiable."},
{id:1442,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, which activity during test completion ensures that future sprints benefit from the current sprint's testing experience?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Documenting lessons learned and updating the regression suite ensures continuous improvement â€” growing the safety net and capturing institutional knowledge for future sprints."},
{id:1443,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"A team tracks 'user story coverage' as a metric. What does this measure?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"User story coverage measures what proportion of stories have test coverage of their acceptance criteria â€” a functional traceability metric ensuring all stories are verifiably addressed."},
{id:1444,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team tracks 'defect injection rate' (defects introduced per story point delivered). Over 6 sprints, this rate has been stable. In sprint 7, it doubles. What is the MOST likely explanation?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"A sudden doubling of defect injection rate signals a structural change â€” major refactors, new technology, or complex changes dramatically increase defect introduction probability."},
{id:1445,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which principle of Agile communication MOST influences how test reports should be structured and delivered?",options:["A. Reports should be as comprehensive and detailed as possible","B. Face-to-face communication is preferred â€” written reports should be lightweight, frequent, and actionable rather than exhaustive","C. Reports must follow IEEE standard templates exactly","D. Only formal written reports count as official communication"],answer:1,explanation:"Agile values the most efficient forms of communication. Test reports should be lightweight and actionable, supplementing (not replacing) face-to-face team communication."},
{id:1446,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's DoD requires 'all automated tests passing in CI.' At sprint end, CI is failing due to a flaky test unrelated to sprint work. What is the correct approach?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Flaky tests undermine CI integrity. The correct response is to fix or quarantine the flaky test, restore CI reliability, and then confirm DoD compliance â€” not to lower standards or ignore the failure."},
{id:1447,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"medium",question:"A 'release readiness checklist' typically includes which of the following items?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"A release readiness checklist systematically confirms quality evidence: testing is complete, defects are within acceptable thresholds, non-functional criteria are met, deployment is planned, and stakeholders have approved."},
{id:1448,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is 'risk appetite' and how does it influence residual risk acceptance decisions?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Risk appetite defines the organization's tolerance for risk. It directly influences how much residual risk can be accepted at release â€” a risk-averse organization requires lower residual risk thresholds than a risk-tolerant one."},
{id:1449,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"hard",question:"During acceptance criteria evaluation, a tester finds that the system meets all written acceptance criteria but has a significant usability issue not captured in any criterion. What should the tester do?",options:["A. Accept the story since all written criteria are met","B. Raise the usability issue as a separate defect or backlog item, accept the story against its written criteria, and recommend improving the acceptance criteria process to capture usability requirements","C. Reject the story because usability issues always block acceptance","D. Rewrite the acceptance criteria to include the usability issue retroactively and fail the story"],answer:1,explanation:"Testers should distinguish between acceptance criteria compliance (story passes what was agreed) and additional quality findings. New findings become backlog items; the acceptance process gets improved prospectively."},
{id:1450,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"hard",question:"In an Agile context, how should the team handle a non-functional requirement for 'zero data loss under network failure conditions'?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Data integrity requirements under failure conditions are high-risk and must be explicitly tested. Agile teams must create testable backlog items with measurable criteria and test them within sprints."},
{id:1451,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An organization wants to define 'smart' exit criteria for a high-stakes financial product. Which set of criteria BEST demonstrates Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound characteristics?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"SMART exit criteria are specific (named thresholds), measurable (numbers), achievable (realistic), relevant (risk and quality-aligned), and time-bound (sprint 10). Vague or subjective criteria fail these dimensions."},
{id:1452,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile test report is challenged by a stakeholder who says the team's green dashboards have never predicted production incidents correctly. The tester defends the metrics as accurate. How should this conflict be resolved?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Metric credibility is earned through demonstrated predictive validity. When metrics consistently fail to predict outcomes, the right response is to validate and redesign the metric set â€” not defend metrics that demonstrably don't work."},
{id:1453,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does a declining 'test effectiveness ratio' over consecutive sprints indicate?",options:["A. The team is finding fewer defects because the code quality is improving","B. The proportion of test cases that find defects is declining, which may indicate the test suite is becoming less effective at finding new defects â€” possibly due to redundant tests or insufficient new test design","C. The team is executing more test cases than needed","D. The sprint velocity is too high"],answer:1,explanation:"A declining test effectiveness ratio (defects found / test cases executed) means the same test effort is finding fewer defects â€” a signal to refresh the test suite with new scenarios targeting unexplored risk areas."},
{id:1454,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"medium",question:"In Agile, what makes a test summary report 'fit for purpose'?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"A fit-for-purpose report is audience-appropriate, concise, timely, and decision-supporting. Format and length should serve communication, not bureaucracy."},
{id:1455,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team has a working agreement that if the CI build is red at sprint end, no stories are accepted as done. In sprint 12, the CI build is red due to an infrastructure failure (not a code defect). The team has verified all story functionality manually. The Scrum Master wants to accept the stories. Is this appropriate, and why?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Working agreements should be respected, but documented exceptions with clear rationale are preferable to rigid application that ignores context. The team should make an explicit decision, document it, and improve the agreement to handle infrastructure failures distinctly."},
{id:1456,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An organization releases to production 20 times per day using continuous deployment. A manager asks: 'How do you know each release is ready?' What is the MOST comprehensive answer?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Continuous deployment at scale requires automated quality gates at every pipeline stage. Manual approval cannot scale to 20 releases/day â€” automated tests, security scans, and canary deployments with automated rollback are the practical mechanism."},
{id:1457,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A tester produces a residual risk report before a major release. The report identifies 3 areas of untested functionality. Management pressures the tester to remove these from the report to avoid 'creating uncertainty.' What is the CORRECT response?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:1,explanation:"Suppressing known quality risks from official documentation violates professional ethics and potentially legal/regulatory requirements. Testers have a professional duty to report objectively. Management pressure does not override this obligation."},
{id:1458,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"extreme",question:"A product owner rewrites acceptance criteria AFTER development is complete to match what was actually built rather than what was originally specified. A tester objects. What principle is violated, and what is the risk?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Retrofitting acceptance criteria to match the build destroys their purpose. They exist to verify that what was built matches what was needed. Changing criteria to match the build means you're testing the system against itself."},
{id:1459,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team working on a healthcare application has never performed accessibility testing. During a release readiness review, a tester raises this as an untested non-functional requirement. Management says 'accessibility wasn't in scope.' What is the MOST appropriate response?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Accessibility is often a legal requirement for healthcare applications. Even if out of scope, the tester must document the untested area as residual risk, note legal implications, and ensure the risk is formally accepted at the appropriate level."},
{id:1460,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"medium",question:"How does the concept of 'sufficient testing' relate to exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"'Sufficient testing' is context-dependent. Exit criteria translate this concept into concrete, measurable thresholds appropriate to the product's risk profile, time constraints, and quality goals."},
{id:1461,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the MAIN risk of declaring test completion prematurely in an Agile sprint?",options:["A. The next sprint will have more stories than it can handle","B. Incomplete or insufficiently tested stories get included in the product increment, accumulating hidden technical and quality debt that manifests as production defects or future rework","C. The CI/CD pipeline will fail immediately after the sprint","D. The sprint retrospective will take longer than usual"],answer:1,explanation:"Premature test completion means stories enter the DoD unchecked, hiding quality debt. This debt compounds across sprints and eventually surfaces as production incidents or massive rework."},
{id:1462,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"easy",question:"An information radiator in an Agile team context is BEST described as:",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Information radiators are large, visible, continuously updated displays in the team area that make project and testing status transparent to the whole team and visiting stakeholders."},
{id:1463,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"A stakeholder asks for a single 'quality score' for a release. A tester explains why a single number is problematic. Which argument is MOST valid?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Composite quality scores hide important information. A high overall score might mask a critical security gap or performance problem. Stakeholders need to understand what dimensions contribute to the score."},
{id:1464,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is 'functional coverage' in the context of Agile testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Functional coverage measures what proportion of the specified functionality (user stories, requirements) has test coverage â€” ensuring all agreed features are verified."},
{id:1465,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a 'defect trend chart' used for in Agile testing?",options:["A. To track the salary progression of the testing team","B. To visualize the rate of defect discovery and resolution over time, helping the team assess whether quality is improving or deteriorating","C. To record the names of all developers who introduced defects","D. To calculate the total cost of all defects in the project"],answer:1,explanation:"Defect trend charts show defect discovery and resolution rates over time. Rising open defects signal quality deterioration; converging discovery/resolution rates indicate stabilization."},
{id:1466,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is the purpose of the Sprint Review in relation to testing and exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"The Sprint Review is the agile sprint exit event â€” stories are demonstrated, the DoD is verified, and the product owner accepts or rejects the increment based on the agreed criteria."},
{id:1467,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"easy",question:"What does a 'go/no-go decision' represent in a release context?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"A go/no-go decision is a formal release gate â€” a structured decision, based on quality evidence and exit criteria, about whether the increment is ready for production deployment."},
{id:1468,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"easy",question:"Which of the following BEST describes 'known unknowns' in the context of residual risk?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"'Known unknowns' are risks the team is aware of but has not fully characterized or mitigated â€” they represent identifiable residual risk that must be assessed and documented."},
{id:1469,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"easy",question:"Why should acceptance criteria be defined BEFORE development begins?",options:["A. To allow developers to start coding immediately without requirements","B. To give the team a shared understanding of what done looks like, enabling development to be targeted at satisfying verifiable criteria rather than the developer's interpretation","C. To prevent testers from writing test cases","D. Because acceptance criteria cannot be changed once written"],answer:1,explanation:"Pre-defined acceptance criteria align the whole team â€” developers build to satisfy them, testers verify against them, and the product owner accepts based on them, reducing misunderstanding and rework."},
{id:1470,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is 'usability testing' and why is it relevant to exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Usability testing evaluates user experience quality. When usability requirements are defined (e.g., 'task completion rate â‰¥ 90%'), they become measurable exit criteria that must be verified before release."},
{id:1471,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"hard",question:"What is the relationship between exit criteria and risk in an Agile project?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Risk-based exit criteria calibrate testing rigor to consequences. Safety-critical and high-risk systems require more stringent, comprehensive criteria than low-risk internal tools."},
{id:1472,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"easy",question:"What is a 'test closure report' in the context of ISTQB?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"A test closure report (test summary report) formally concludes a testing phase, documenting what was done, results, exit criteria evaluation, and lessons learned for continuous improvement."},
{id:1473,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Reporting",difficulty:"medium",question:"Which of the following is an example of a 'push' reporting approach in Agile testing?",options:["A. Stakeholders access a live test dashboard whenever they want","B. The test team proactively sends daily test status emails or updates to stakeholders without being asked","C. Testers wait for stakeholders to request reports before producing them","D. Automated tests self-report directly to the product owner"],answer:1,explanation:"Push reporting means the team proactively sends information to stakeholders. Pull reporting means stakeholders access information on demand. Agile teams often use both â€” push for critical updates, pull for detailed data via dashboards."},
{id:1474,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What does 'technical debt' have to do with quality metrics and exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Technical debt degrades code quality, increases defect rates, makes tests brittle, and erodes coverage â€” all of which affect quality metrics and make exit criteria progressively harder to achieve without addressing the debt."},
{id:1475,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is 'mutation testing' and how does it relate to coverage metrics?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Mutation testing goes beyond coverage â€” it checks whether tests can actually detect faults. A test suite with 100% branch coverage might still fail to detect mutations if assertions are weak, making mutation score a richer quality metric."},
{id:1476,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is a 'defect prediction model' and how is it used in Agile testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Defect prediction models use historical data to estimate residual defect counts. They help teams make informed decisions about whether testing has been sufficient or whether more effort is needed before release."},
{id:1477,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"hard",question:"A test summary report states that all exit criteria were met, yet the product owner rejects the release. What is the MOST likely explanation?",options:["A. The product owner is acting in bad faith","B. The exit criteria, although met, may not have captured all of the product owner's acceptance requirements â€” there may be a gap between the formally defined criteria and the product owner's actual expectations","C. Test summary reports always lead to release approval","D. Exit criteria automatically guarantee product owner acceptance"],answer:1,explanation:"Technical exit criteria and business acceptance are related but distinct. It's possible to meet all formally defined testing criteria while failing to meet the product owner's broader business expectations not captured in those criteria."},
{id:1478,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"medium",question:"Why should the Definition of Done be agreed by the WHOLE team, not just the testers?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"The DoD is a whole-team quality commitment. If only testers define it, other roles may not feel ownership or understand implications. Shared agreement creates shared accountability."},
{id:1479,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Release Readiness",difficulty:"medium",question:"What role does automated testing play in enabling frequent releases in Agile?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Automation is the enabling capability for frequent Agile releases. Without automation, the regression testing burden of frequent releases would be unsustainable for manual testing alone."},
{id:1480,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Residual Risk",difficulty:"medium",question:"How should a tester communicate residual risk to a non-technical product owner?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Risk communication to non-technical stakeholders must be business-focused â€” translating technical findings into user impact, business consequences, probability, and available mitigations for informed decision-making."},
{id:1481,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Acceptance Criteria Evaluation",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the difference between 'verification' and 'validation' in the context of acceptance criteria evaluation?",options:["A. Verification and validation are the same process with different names","B. Verification checks whether the system was built correctly (meeting specified acceptance criteria); validation checks whether the right system was built (meeting actual user needs)","C. Verification is done by developers; validation is done only by external auditors","D. Validation only applies to hardware products"],answer:1,explanation:"Verification (Are we building the thing right?) evaluates against acceptance criteria. Validation (Are we building the right thing?) evaluates against actual user needs. Both are necessary for a quality release."},
{id:1482,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is 'soak testing' and when is it relevant to exit criteria?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"Soak testing (endurance testing) reveals issues like memory leaks, resource exhaustion, and performance degradation under sustained load â€” critical for systems with reliability/availability exit criteria."},
{id:1483,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Exit Criteria",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team is working under extreme time pressure. A manager suggests temporarily suspending exit criteria to accelerate release. What is the MOST appropriate response?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Exit criteria can be adjusted â€” but only through a formal, documented process with explicit stakeholder risk acceptance. Informal suspension without documentation is a governance and quality failure."},
{id:1484,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Completion",difficulty:"medium",question:"What is the purpose of a 'test log' and how does it support test completion evaluation?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Test logs provide the objective evidence needed to evaluate test completion â€” without execution records, completion claims are unverifiable and audit-unfriendly."},
{id:1485,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Quality Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"An Agile team uses 'happiness metrics' (team satisfaction scores) as one quality metric. A skeptic questions its validity. Which argument BEST supports including it?",options:["A. Happiness metrics have no place in professional testing","B. Research shows that team satisfaction and psychological safety correlate with quality outcomes â€” motivated, engaged teams with low fear of failure produce higher quality software, making team health a leading quality indicator","C. Happiness metrics replace the need for technical quality metrics","D. Only managers need to track team satisfaction"],answer:1,explanation:"Team health is a legitimate leading quality indicator. Distressed, disengaged, or fearful teams produce lower quality software. Monitoring team satisfaction as a leading indicator complements technical metrics."},
{id:1486,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Test Summary Report",difficulty:"medium",question:"What should a tester include in the 'recommendations' section of a test summary report?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"The recommendations section drives continuous improvement â€” identifying specific process improvements, areas for additional test investment, and mitigations for residual risk found during the sprint."},
{id:1487,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Coverage Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"Why might a team achieve high code coverage but low risk coverage simultaneously?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:3,explanation:"Code coverage is structural; risk coverage is scenario-based. You can achieve 100% statement coverage with synthetic tests that miss the real-world high-risk scenarios that matter most to the business."},
{id:1488,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Defect Metrics",difficulty:"hard",question:"What does it mean if the 'defect resolution time' metric is significantly longer for defects found in integration testing compared to unit testing?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:0,explanation:"Later-stage defects involve more complex root causes spanning multiple components. This demonstrates the 'shift left' principle â€” finding defects earlier (in unit testing) reduces resolution complexity and cost."},
{id:1489,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Sprint Exit",difficulty:"hard",question:"A team's Definition of Done evolves during a project. An old sprint's stories were accepted under a weaker DoD. Should these stories be retroactively held to the new, stronger DoD?",options:["A. Yes â€” all stories must always meet the current DoD regardless of when they were completed","B. Stories accepted under the DoD in place at the time are properly done for that sprint. The stronger DoD applies to future work. However, gaps in previously accepted stories should be identified as backlog items or technical debt and addressed in future sprints","C. The DoD should never change once set at the beginning of a project","D. Only the Scrum Master can decide whether to retroactively apply DoD changes"],answer:1,explanation:"DoD changes are prospective. Past stories were completed in good faith under the prevailing standard. New standards apply to new work. Identified gaps from old work become explicit technical debt for the backlog."},
{id:1490,chapter:"Evaluating Exit Criteria and Reporting",topic:"Non-Functional Testing",difficulty:"extreme",question:"An Agile team must evaluate exit criteria for a machine learning model integrated into a critical decision-making system. Traditional functional and non-functional test criteria are insufficient. Which additional considerations are MOST relevant to exit criteria for this type of system?",options:["A. ","B. ","C. ","D. "],answer:2,explanation:"ML/AI systems require specialized exit criteria beyond traditional software testing: model performance metrics, bias/fairness evaluation, explainability, distribution shift robustness, and adversarial robustness â€” areas not addressed by conventional functional or non-functional testing criteria."}
